history.content:
All of them sound like pretty similar workload to me. CS 170 and EE 126 are very high workload courses, and likelihood is, you will spend most of your time there. In my opinion, CS 170 and EE 126 will definitely be a higher workload than CS 70 and CS 61C, because their homework are very time consuming. If you want to get the most out of CS 170 and EE 126 (which, by the way, are all very important courses, especially if you are trying to do anything ML - and even if you aren't!), I would even recommend leaving out Math 110/Data 100/CS 188. 

I think Math 110, Data 100 and CS 188 are pretty similar in workload, though I did hear that Data 100 and CS 188 became heavier recently. 

From what I know, EE 127, Math 104 do not rely on material from the aforementioned courses, though they definitely provide you with extra mathematical intuition and maturity.

children.subject:
Ok. However, Data 100 and CS188 aren't really comparable in work right?

Actually, in terms of comparing work how would work compare between Data100, Math 110, CS188?

history.content:
Thoughts/opinions for workload of each? I guess as long as I get an approximate estimate of all those three schedules I should be able to figure it out. I think I would like the first schedule in the title because of the workload but was wondering about the other class combo workloads, and also their relative usefulness for the future. I regret not taking Math 110 this semester (I'm only in 70 61C but I don't like 61C). 

There's also the alternative of taking it lighter this spring but I also don't know what the direct consequences of that is in terms of class scheduling for the future

I think in Fall I am thinking of taking EE127, a programming class, and Math 104...
